text.tspan: Wealth Manager
Recent Commentary on M&A
Ameriprise Financial
-Over the past year, AMP has articulated a cautious and targeted approach to M&A, focusing primarily on advisor recruitment and practice
acquisitions rather than large-scale corporate acquisitions.
-AMP noted that the current market for wealth management acquisitions is overpriced, with CEO James Cracchiolo stating in Jan '25 that
"the market is a little bit pricey right now" and that "private equity has bid up things", resulting in a more challenging M&A enviornment and
increased prioritization around organic growth
BNY
-BNY has consistently emphasized a "very high bar" for M&A transactions, particularly for larger deals - with the focus on organic growth. At
2Q25 earnings, management stated any potential M&A deal "would have to make a ton of sense" with "a lot of conviction and execution."
The company points to their acquisition of Archer in 2024 as an example of their M&A approach - a capability-focused acquisition that helps
them "go faster" rather than having to build capabilities internally.
-"We don't really have anything on the horizon at the moment that we're really looking out for, but we're always trying to learn and look for
opportunity and see where our gaps are and how we can grow organically or inorganically." CFO (Sept. '25)
Citigroup
-There has been limited commentary on M&A, but scaling the Wealth business is a strategic priority for Citi, notably hiring Andy Sieg from
BAC to lead the business. Partnerships seem more likely than inorganic growth. Recently, Citi announced a partnership with BlackRock
(Sept'25): BlackRock will manage approx. $80B in assets for thousands of Citi Wealth clients under a new portfolio offering called "Citi
Portfolio Solutions powered by BlackRock."
Goldman Sachs
-GS has stressed that, "The bar to do something significant has to be very, very high." That said, if GS were to do a deal, the focus area
would likely be in the Asset and Wealth business, per the CEO (Sept '25). "If there are opportunities that can accelerate our asset and wealth
management strategy and kind of solidify the position of that franchise, we're going to think about them. We've obviously got capital to
deploy."
-GS recently announced a strategic partnership with TROW, in which GS would invest $1B equity in the company (up to 3.5% ownership) as
part of a collaboration to offer retirement and wealth management products. The partnership gives Goldman "distribution into retirement
channels with... the premier retirement platform" and creates opportunities for "co-branded opportunities for investors around their
retirement portfolios."
JPMorgan
-JPM has consistently expressed openness to strategic M&A opportunities, while maintaining a disciplined approach that prioritizes organic
growth. CEO Jamie Dimon has emphasized that while acquisitions are "always on the table," they must meet high strategic, financial, and
cultural standards.
-While not specific to the asset & wealth management business, the CFO recently acknowleged that inorganic opportunities are 'always on
the table' particularly given their excess capital position.
LPL Financial
-LPLA has been the most active in M&A among US brokers. Over the last twelve months, LPLA has closed acquisitions of Commonwealth,
The Investment Center, and Atria Wealth Solutions, adding over $400b to their platform.
-LPLA has explicitly stated that M&A is a key part of its growth strategy, noting that, "Rising cost and complexity is making it harder for
smaller players to effectively compete," and that, "Consolidation can drive value creation."
Northern Trust
-NTRS company has made clear its commitment to independence following recent merger speculation. The company has maintained a
cautious stance towards deals, emphasizing a focus on organic growth while remaining selectively open to capability-driven acquisitions
that align with strategic priorities.
-"If we were to do anything in M&A, it would be in the wealth and asset management space, but to be honest with you, we are so focused on
organic growth right now that it really isn't a top priority for us." -CFO (Sept '25)
-"As you look at the Wealth Management business... so capability-wise, I think they're focused on alternative investments...It doesn't have to
be an acquisition, right? There are partnerships. There are joint ventures. There's other ways of doing it, distribution agreements, huge focus
for Jason [President of Wealth Management] right now." -CFO (Sept '25)
Raymond James
- RJF maintains that the bar is high for M&A; all targets must fit three criteria: 1) cultural fit - target must be emblamatic of family first
culture; 2) strategic fit - where one plus one gives us a chance of being more than two; 3) suitable from a financial perspective.
- Outside of the wealth business, RJF has expressed interest in expanding investment banking M&A capabilities via acquisition and
improving asset management capabilites, though noted that most opportunties that have been presented do not necessarily bring good
organic growth profiles.
Robinhood
-Over the past year, HOOD has articulated a clear M&A strategy focused on disciplined acquisitions that accelerate its product roadmap and
expand its global financial ecosystem. The company has completed several strategic acquisitions while maintaining a consistent approach
to its M&A philosophy.
-HOOD M&A strategy to date has been around adding new capabilities or geographical footprints rather than expanding pre-existing
verticals. The bias has been towards smaller, more efficient businesses that can scale quickly... for example, in May 2025, HOOD
announced the acquisition of WonderFi, a Canadian digital asset provider in a $179m all-cash deal.
Charles Schwab
-SCHW commentary around M&A has been relatively muted recently, perhaps unsuprising given the large $26b all-stock acquisition of
Ameritrade that closed in 2020… mgmt recently integrated the two platforms and has begun realizing benefits from the transaction this year
UBS
-Based on recent statements and actions, UBS appears to be focused primarily on integrating Credit Suisse's assets rather than pursuing
new major M&A deals in its asset and wealth management business. The bank is currently engaged in significant restructuring and
integration efforts following its acquisition of Credit Suisse.
US Bancorp
-"Outside of sort of big bank M&A, we are always open to sort of bolt-on M&A. We do that very well, too. We see that more in the realm of
payments or institutional world, and that's opportunistic, and we are always looking at any properties that might augment either scale or the
product capability, but the focus right now is organic growth." - CEO (Sept '25)
Wells Fargo
-The Fed-imposed asset cap on WFC had put limits on the firm's ability to do M&A. The CFO recently stressed a hig bar for M&A in general,
and that there's a lot of opportunity for organic growth within wealth manaement.
-"Could there be interesting opportunities to do something inorganic? For sure, if something comes up, we will certainly take a look at it.
There'll be a high bar as we sort of think about the opportunities. But you can certainly think about adding capabilities from a payments or a
product perspective. You could look at broader sets of things." - CFO (Sept '25)
-Note: In 2021, Wells divested its asset management business (WFAM) for $2.1B, explicitly aimed at allowing Wells to concentrate on its
wealth management business.
